Introduction:
Thromboembolic events (TE), including deep vein thrombosis (DVT) and pulmonary embolism (PE), are relevant complications in neurosurgery, particularly following meningioma resection. Several factors have been implicated, such as advanced age, obesity, venous sinus invasion, peritumoral edema, corticosteroid use, and tumor-induced coagulation changes.

Objectives:
Primary: To determine the incidence of postoperative TE in patients undergoing meningioma surgery.
Secondary: To identify risk factors associated with TE and to develop a practical clinical tool to stratify patients by risk.

Materials and Methods:
A retrospective cohort study of 87 patients undergoing meningioma surgery (n=85 after exclusions). Clinical, tumor-related, and perioperative variables were analyzed using descriptive statistics, univariate comparisons, and multivariate logistic regression. A predictive model and an interactive risk calculator were developed.

Results:
The incidence of TE was 16.5% (14/85). Significant associated factors included age (p=0.0007), BMI (p=0.0269), tumor size (p=0.0286), venous sinus invasion (p=0.0377), peritumoral edema (p=0.0184), and corticosteroid use (p=0.0234). In multivariate analysis, only age remained an independent predictor (p=0.0097). The predictive model demonstrated excellent performance (AUC = 0.99), enabling risk stratification through a simplified clinical rule based on five variables.

Conclusions:
Postoperative TE in meningioma patients is influenced by clinical, tumor-related, and perioperative factors. Age emerged as the primary independent predictor. The predictive tool developed may assist in risk stratification and prophylaxis optimization.

Keywords: Meningioma, thromboembolism, deep vein thrombosis, pulmonary embolism, corticosteroids.

"""
